@node "Document_1" "Introduction"
@{b}Introduction@{ub} 

Convert V1.0 is a simple WorkBench units converter.  

WorkBench 2.04+ and the @{"ClassAct" link "Document_5" 0} boopsi gadget classes are required to use
Convert.

Convert has 7 different categories of Measurement:

1.   @{u}Measure@{uu} - Inches, Feet, Yards, Miles..etc.

2.   @{u}Area@{uu} - Square Inches, Square Feet, Square Metres...etc.

3.   @{u}Volume@{uu} - Litres, Gallons, Cubic Metres...etc.

4.   @{u}Pressure@{uu} - Pounds/Square Inch, Kilopascals...etc.

5.   @{u}Weight@{uu} - Ounces, Kilograms, Tonnes...etc.

6.   @{u}Energy@{uu} - Kilowatts, Horsepower, BTU/hr...etc.

7.  @{u} Velocity@{uu} - Feet/Second, Knots, Metres/Second...etc.


I hope you find it useful.
@endnode

@node "Document_2" "Installation"
@{b}Installation@{ub}

There are no special installation instructions for Convert; copy Convert and
this file to the directory of your choice. 

It is assumed that you have already obtained and properly installed the
ClassAct Boopsi gadget classes.  If not you may obtain these required files
@{"here" link "Document_5" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Document_3" "Usage"
@{b}Usage@{ub}

Convert can be run either from the WorkBench or from the Shell/Cli.  There
are currently no Tool types or shell arguments.  To run Convert just double
click on its icon from Workbench or type "convert" from the shell.  

@{u}Converting Units@{uu}

Using Convert is really self explanatory but just in case, I'll provide a
simple example to follow:

Problem: Convert 180 lbs to kilograms.

Solution:

1.   Select category -> Weight (with mouse or 'W' from the keyboard).

2.   Select the 'Pounds' String gadget (or 'd' keyboard shortcut).

3.   Enter '180' and press RETURN.

4.   The display indicates 81.6475 kilograms (as well as 6 other weight
     units also equivalent to 180 pounds).
@endnode

